Title: Love in the Time of Cholera
Review: It was an interesting take on the usual love story. And what I think put it over the edge for me in comparison to other novels that are centered on a singular love story is that the middle was actually enjoyable. And I don't mean to say that I don't like other novels with love stories or that the other ones are bad. But I sort of expected the classic story: boy-meets-girl, long interlude of sometime unnecessary problems, boy-gets-girl. And the take on the story and the compelling protagonist kept me entertained the whole way.

Review:
If you check out my other reviews you'll see how much I love Hemingway, and I have this book to thank for it. It's so good I read it like 3 times in one week, I kept saying "I'm gonna stop now so I could enjoy it over the week" but I couldn't put it down. And it is so short that even if you are not reading a lot every day, you'll finish it in no time.

His style fits the narrative in such a way that I don't believe I had ever seen. The way in which he paints the picture that is Santiago's journey is so brilliant you could read this book just for that. But by the end you have such deep connection with Santiago that every little plot twist has emotional payoff.

Title: The Prophet
Review:
I heard about this book from the Mr. and Mrs. Smith show on Amazon Prime, where it serves as a significant plot point.

I adored this book and I saved several quotes for posterity. My biggest overarching thought about this book is a sense of connectedness with humanity. It's crazy to me that one could live in such different eras can converge on what life is truly all about. More specifically, I will have this book in mind when people say "it was a different time" to explain away the wrongdoings of the people who came before it. Well, there were at least some people (such as the author here) who had compassion, empathy, and mindfulness figured out 100 years ago

A Farewell to Arms
Review:
This was the first Hemingway book I read since The Old Man and the Sea, and I was sorta struggling with the first chapters. But as soon as Catherine Barkley comes in, it all changes.

This is clearly, the most personal of Hemingway books as it shows by the way he talks about Catherine. He pours on this book a lot of his experiences and desires. For example, he was left by a woman who he met at the War when he was very young and you can tell by the way the protagonist talks with Catherine how insecure Hemingway was about women.

And the final chapter, literally breathtaking.

Doctor Faustus: The Life of the German Composer Adrian Leverkuhn as Told by a Friend
For Whom the Bell Tolls
Review:
This book is great throughout. But there's one chapter (and I won't spoil anything) that everybody that has read the book can point out as beautifully written and heart-wrenching while still being as economical with words as Hemingway is. The best part about this book is that it has the first female character that Hemingway does not under-write. It deals with such technique about its mature themes (war, death, suicide) that it's, at the same time, easy to read and emotionally appealing.

I really recommend this one.

Review: His style is so compelling to me that even books with plots that were so unappealing to me (like this one) can be very enjoyable. So, read it if you like Hemingway, if you don't or you haven't read Hemingway I would recommend starting with The Old Man and The Sea and going from there.
